\begin_layout Section
The Large Hadron Collider
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Large Hadron Collider (LHC) is a proton-proton storage ring at the European
 Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN) in Geneva, Switzerland.
 It is built underground and has a circumference of approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $27\,\mathrm{km}$
\end_inset

.
 The performance goal is a center-of-mass energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{s}=14\,\mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

 at a luminosity of 
\begin_inset Formula $L=10^{34}\,{\textstyle \frac{1}{\mathrm{cm^{2}s}}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LHCmachine"

\end_inset

.
 The proton beams can also be switched to ion beams.
 Here, the aimed peak luminosity is 
\begin_inset Formula $L=10^{27}\,{\textstyle \frac{1}{\mathrm{cm^{2}s}}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{s}=2.76\,\mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LHCmachine"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-CERN-accelerator"

\end_inset

 shows the accelerator complex with the LHC, its experiments and the pre-acceler
ator chain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acceleration of protons starts at the Linac2.
 It continues with the Proton Synchrotron Booster (PSB), the Proton Synchrotron
 (PS), the Super Proton Synchrotron (SPS), and finally the protons are injected
 into the LHC at an energy per proton of 
\begin_inset Formula $450\,\mathrm{GeV}$
