\begin_layout Standard
Four major experiments are using the LHC beam collisions for analysis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ALICE (A Large Ion Collider Experiment) is a detector for studying heavy-ion
 collisions and the properties of quark-gluon plasma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ATLAS is a general purpose detector with a special donut-shaped magnet system.
 Its scientific program covers the physics of the Higgs boson, super-symmetry
 and extra dimensions besides others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CMS (Compact Muon Solenoid) is also a general purpose detector with a wide-rangi
ng physics program.
 Its design involves different technical solutions compared to ATLAS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LHC-b (Large Hadron Collider beauty Experiment) has a forward sub-detector
 system.
 Besides others it probes the CP violation in B hadrons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After a breakdown during the first tests in September 2008, the full operation
 of the LHC started on 20th November 2009 with successfully circulating
 beams at injection energy.
 In March 2010, the targeted beam energy of 
