\end_inset

.
 In 2012 the center-of-mass energy has been raised to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{s}=8\,\mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The CMS Experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Compact Muon Solenoid (CMS) is a general-purpose detector developed
 to record the proton-proton collisions at the high luminosity that the
 LHC provides.
 The physics program of the CMS collaboration involves the search for the
 Higgs boson, the discovery or exclusion of supersymmetric particles (SUSY),
 new heavy vector bosons, and extra dimensions.
 Besides that, precision measurements of the SM are performed like studies
 of QCD, electroweak and top quark physics.
 During heavy-ion runs, the properties of strongly-interacting nuclear matter
 is investigated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CMS detector has been designed with a cylindrical symmetry around the
 beam pipe.
 It is 
\begin_inset Formula $21.5\,\mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

 long and has a diameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $14.6\,\mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-CMS-Experiment"

\end_inset

 shows the CMS detector and its subsystems which are mainly the inner tracker
 (pixel and silicon tracker), the electromagnetic calorimeter, the hadron
 calorimeter, the superconduction solenoid, and the muon detectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CMS uses the following coordinate system.
 The interaction point (IP) is the origin.
 The z-axis matches the beamline.
 The x-axis points towards the center of the LHC ring and the y-axis points
 upwards, orthogonal to x and z.
 To reflect the cylindrical symmetry of the detector, one instead often
 uses the pseudorapidity 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=-\ln{\textstyle \left(\tan\frac{\theta}{2}\right)}$
\end_inset

 with the azimuthal angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 between the z-axis and the xy-plane, and the polar angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 inside the xy-plane.
\end_layout

