\begin_layout Paragraph*
Inner tracking system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Around the IP, the tracking system is placed.
 It is 
\begin_inset Formula $540\,\mathrm{cm}$
\end_inset

 long and has an outer radius of 
\begin_inset Formula $r=110\,\mathrm{cm}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system itself is divided into three regions.
 This is due to the expected particle flux which decreases radially.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $r\approx10\,\mathrm{cm}$
\end_inset

 pixel detectors are placed with a size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{100}\times\mathrm{150}\,\mu\mathrm{m^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 In the next region around 
\begin_inset Formula $20<r<55\,\mathrm{cm}$
\end_inset

 silicon microstrip detectors can be used due to the lower particle flux.
 They have a minimal cell size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{10\, cm}\times\mathrm{80}\,\mu\mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

.
 In the last region of the tracking system, larger-pitch silicon microstrips
 are installed.
 Their cell size is at minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{25\, cm}\times\mathrm{180}\,\mu\mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

.
 With these components, the tracking system is able to reconstruct particle
 tracks even in the high particle density environment of heavy-ion collisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Electromagnetic calorimeter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electromagnetic calorimeter (ECAL) is composed out of lead tungstate
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{PbWO_{4}}$
\end_inset

) scintillating crystals.
 The crystal material was chosen due to its fast response time (within 
\begin_inset Formula $25\,\mathrm{\mathrm{ns}}$
\end_inset

) and radiation hardness (up to 
\begin_inset Formula $10\,\mathrm{Mrad}$
\end_inset

).
 61200 crystals are installed in the central barrel part and an additional
 7324 are placed in each of the two endcaps.
 The light yield of the crystals is rather low.
 Therefore photodetectors with intrinsic gain are applied.
 For amplification silicon avalanche photodiodes (APDs) are used in the
 barrel and vacuum phototriodes (VPTs) are used in the endcaps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The complete ECAL covers a pseudorapidity range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|\leq3.0$
\end_inset

.
 The transition region between barrel and endcap is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|=1.479$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Its energy resolution can be parameterized 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cmsperformance"

\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\sigma_{E}^{2}}{E}\right)=\underbrace{\left(\frac{2.8\%\cdot\sqrt{E}}{\sqrt{E}}\right)^{2}}_{\mathrm{stochastic\, term}}+\underbrace{\left(\frac{0.12\,\mathrm{GeV}}{E}\right)^{2}}_{\mathrm{noise\, term}}+\underbrace{\left(0.3\%\right)^{2}}_{\mathrm{constant\, term}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Hadron calorimeter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hadron calorimeter (HCAL) surrounds the the ECAL system.
 It is divided into four parts: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hadron barrel (HB) is installed inside the magnetic coil, and covers
 a pseudorapidity range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|\leq1.4$
\end_inset

.
 The hadron outer (HO) is located at the outer vacuum tank of the coil.
 It has a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|\leq1.26$
\end_inset

.
 The hadron endcap (HE) can measure in a pseudorapidity range of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.3\leq\left|\eta\right|\leq3.0$
\end_inset

 and the hadron forward (HF) covers a pseudorapidity range of 
\begin_inset Formula $3.0\leq\left|\eta\right|\leq5.0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The HCAL consists of brass as absorber material which has a short interaction
 length.
 It provides a good particle containment, which is needed for the detection
 of missing transverse energy.
 To maximize the absorber space inside the barrel, plastic scintillator
 tiles with embedded wavelength-shifting (WLS) fibers are used as active
 medium.
 They require only a minimum of space to carry the light to the readout
 system of multi-channel hybrid photodiodes (HPDs).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The HCAL in combination with the ECAL can measure hadrons with a resolution
 of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\sigma_{E}}{E}\right)^{2}\approx\left(\frac{100\%\cdot\sqrt{E}}{\sqrt{E}}\right)^{2}+\left(5\%\right)^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More about the HCAL performance and how it affects the missing transverse
 energy resolution can be found in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hcalperformance"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Solenoid coil
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A large superconducting solenoid coil for bending of charged particle tracks
 is used.
 Supplied with a current of 
\begin_inset Formula $19.5\,\mathrm{kA}$
\end_inset

, it generates a field of 
\begin_inset Formula $3.8\,\mathrm{T}$
\end_inset

 at the IP .
 This provides a momentum resolution of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta p}{p}\approx10\%\qquad\mathrm{(at}\, p=\mathrm{1\, TeV)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can unambiguously determine the charge of a muon up to 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1\,\mathrm{TeV}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

