\begin_layout Section
Reconstruction of Physics Objects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Particle-Flow Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Particle-Flow (PF) algorithm aims at precisely identifing particle types
 and their momenta by exploiting all detector sub systems.
 It creates particle hypotheses within an event by combining information
 from charged-particle tracks, calorimetry hits and muon tracks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "particleflow"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm starts with the tracker information by first singling out
 tracks with very tight criteria originating closely from the IP.
 On the remaining tracks, iteratively looser criteria are applied for selection.
 In the calorimeters, hits are clustered.
 This is performed by finding cells with high energy maxima (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cluster seeds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Then, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

topological clusters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are constructed by combining the seeds with adjacent cells if they measured
 an energy over a certain threshold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One expects that a particle leads to a charged-particle track and/or hits
 several calorimeter clusters as well as one or no track in the muon system.
 These pieces of information are linked to reconstruct each single observed
 particle while possible double counting has to be taken care of.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Muon Identification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Muons can be identified in three ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For muons with low momenta, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Tracker Muon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is defined by extrapolating tracker tracks into the muon system.
 For this, energy loss and possible multiple scattering of muons from the
 tracker to the muon system are taken into account.
 At least one segment of the muon system (DT or CSC) needs to be in coincidence
 with the extrapolation to claim this muon hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Global Muon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is reconstructed through a fit to the inner tracker and the muon system
 data.
 This combination method improves the muon momentum resolution above a transvers
e momentum of 
\begin_inset Formula $200\,\mathrm{GeV}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Standalone-Muon track only
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is claimed if both previously described methods fail.
 This is the case if the muon is observed only in the muon system.
 Due to the high tracker efficiency, those muons often originate from cosmic
 rays and not from an interaction at the IP 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "muonID"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Particle-Flow algorithm categorizes the muons further.
 If there is less than a 10% fraction of the muon's transverse momentum
 in a cone of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\Delta\eta^{2}+\Delta\phi^{2}}<0.3$
\end_inset

 around the muon, the muon is labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

isolated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The remaining 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-isolated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 muons are labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

loose
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pfmuon"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Missing transverse Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the Particle-Flow reconstruction, the missing transverse energy can
 be calculated.
 Due to the conversation of momentum, the net transverse momentum has to
 be zero after a collision.
 One can obtain the missing transverse energy from the mirrored net momentum
 of all reconstructed particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Depending on the physics analysis, the missing transverse energy is often
 used to support the construction of hypotheses about particles that cannot
 be detected directly in CMS, like neutrinos or SUSY particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jet Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A jet is a group of particles originating from hadronization of partons.
 Jet algorithms are used to group reconstructed particles to jets.
 By summing up the momenta within a jet, an inference about the parton momentum
 can be made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nowadays, the mainly used jet algorithms are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{k_{T}}$
\end_inset

, the anti-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{k_{T}}$
\end_inset

 and the Seedless Infrared-Safe Cone (SIS-Cone) algorithms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "antiKT,siscone"

\end_inset

.
 Each one is considered infrared- and collinear-safe.
 Figure 
