\begin_layout Standard
Soft gluons emitted from a parton during the hadronization produce additional
 particles with low momenta that should be clustered into the jet.
 However, lowly energetic particles originating from other interactions
 should be left out.
 This infrared accumulation may sum up and has a significantly incorrect
 input to the jet.
 Suppressing this behavior by setting a minimum momentum threshold (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

seed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) for the clustering will lead to the wrong result in the collinear limit.
 Here, jet algorithms should not change their result, if one particle with
 high momentum is splitted into many collinear particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the CMS reconstruction, the anti-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{k_{T}}$
\end_inset

 algorithm is used.
 It operates on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proto-jets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which are initially the reconstructed particles.
 Its core procedure is the iterative calculation of the distances
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d_{ij} & =\min\left(\frac{1}{p_{\mathrm{T,}\, i}^{2}},\,\frac{1}{p_{\mathrm{T,}\, j}^{2}}\right)\cdot\frac{\Delta_{ij}}{R^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{i}=\frac{1}{p_{\mathrm{T,}\, i}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

between all proto-jets 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ij}=\sqrt{\Delta\eta^{2}+\Delta\phi^{2}}$
\end_inset

 denotes the distance in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\phi$
\end_inset

-plane between the two proto-jets and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

 denotes their transverse momenta.
 After the first calculation of the two distances 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

, a proto-jet 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is considered as a jet if 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}<d_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 This jet is then removed from the next iteration.
 In the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}>d_{ij}$
\end_inset

 the two proto-jets 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are merged to a new proto-jet by summing their four-momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\mathrm{new}}=p^{i}+p^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The algorithm continues until all proto-jets have been considered as jets.
 Hereby, the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 controls the cone sizes of the resulting jets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identification of Jets from b-Quarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jet algorithms can not determine the original flavor of a hadronized quark.
 However, the relatively long decay time of B hadrons can be exploited for
 identifying jets that originate from bottom quarks.
 In a proton-proton collision, the hard interaction is often boosted with
 respect to the lab frame.
 If a long-lived particle such as a B hadron is produced, it will fly a
 measurable distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 from the primary interaction vertex before decaying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CMS reconstruction uses, amongst others, the track-counting method.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

b-tag
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 discriminator is constructed by using the significance 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{\sigma_{d}}{d}}$
\end_inset

 that the n-th good track of a jet is not from the primary vertex 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "btagging"

\end_inset

.
 The analysis in this thesis uses the Track Counting High Purity (TCHP)
 algorithm, which is based on the significance of the third track of a jet.
\end_layout

