\begin_layout Subsection
Toolkit for Multivariate Data Analysis with ROOT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Toolkit for Multivariate Data Analysis with ROOT (TMVA) is a C++ analysis
 framework.
 It hosts various algorithms for multivariate classification.
 In high energy physics, such classifications in high dimensional spaces
 are often used to further discriminate between signal and background events
 after preselection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To setup a discriminator for classification, the classifier algorithm is
 first trained and tested with simulated signal and background events.
 For evaluation, statistically independent simulated samples are needed
 for a bias-free comparison with actual data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next paragraphs describe the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Projective Likelihood Estimator
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boosted Decision and Regression Tree
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algorithms, which are applied in the analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Projective Likelihood Estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each event in the evaluation, the Likelihood ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{\mathrm{L}}(i)=\frac{\mathrm{L_{S}}(i)}{\mathrm{L_{S}}(i)+\mathrm{L_{B}}(i)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is defined.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{L_{S(B)}}$
\end_inset

 is the product probability over all input variables from the training that
 the event is signal- (background-) like.
 The resulting classifier ranges from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 (background-like) to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 (signal-like).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method has been chosen because it is not sensitive to correlations
 within the input variables.
 This is required in order to not alter artificially the signal shape if
 the classifier is used to select a signal enhanced phase space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Boosted Decision Tree (BDT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A decision tree tries to identify signal- or background-like phase spaces
 within the n-dimensional input variables space.
 This is performed by sequentially cutting on the variables to select a
 signal enhanced region.
 However a single trained decision tree can be very unstable due to statistical
 fluctuations in the training samples.
 Therefore, many decision trees are constructed.
 A stabilized discriminator is derived by a majority vote over all trees.
 Boosting increases the discriminator stability further by applying additional
 weight factors for each decision tree based on its performance.
 The Boosted Decision Tree (BDT) discriminator can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y(\vec{x})=\frac{1}{N_{\mathrm{trees}}}\cdot\sum_{j}^{N_{\mathrm{trees}}}\ln\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\cdot h_{j}(\vec{x}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\mathrm{trees}}$
\end_inset

 counts the number of decision trees.
 The decision result of an individual tree is 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}$
\end_inset

 for an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 which takes the values 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 for signal-like and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}=-1$
\end_inset

 for background-like events.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{j}$
\end_inset

 notes the additional boosting weight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The used AdaBoost algorithm calculates the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{j}$
\end_inset

 from the misclassification rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha=\frac{1-\epsilon}{\epsilon}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Through the normalization to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\alpha_{j}=\mathrm{const}$
\end_inset

 the BDT discriminator ranges between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TMVAGuide"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BDT has been chosen for its stability and high discrimination power.
 It exploits also correlations between the input variables.
\end_layout

